<subsection xml:id="subsec-measures_of_central_tendency">
    <title>measures of central tendency</title>
    <p>
        Measures of central tendency are statistical tools used to summarize a set of data by identifying the central or typical value around which the data are distributed. 
        They help us understand the average or middle point of the data.
    </p>
    <p>
        There are three main meausures of central tendency
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Mean (Arithmetic Average)
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The sum of all values divided by the number of values.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Mean = } \frac{\sum_{}^{}x}{n} </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Median
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The middle value when data is arranged in order.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If <m>n</m> is odd: median = middle value.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If <m>n</m> is even: median = average of two middle values.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Mode
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The value that appears most frequently.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>

        
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>{\color{black} \textbf{Work in groups}}</m>
        </p>
    
        <p>
            A teacher recorded the ages of 45 students in a school. The ages are:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>12, 13, 12, 14, 13, 12, 15, 14, 13, 12, 14, 13, 12, 13, 14,</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m> 12, 14, 12, 13, 14, 13, 12, 14, 13, 15,  12, 13, 15, 14,12,</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m> 13, 12, 14, 13, 12, 15, 13, 14, 12, 13, 14, 12, 15, 14, 13</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the mean age of the students.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Explain what the mean represents in this case.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m>{\color{black} \textbf{Key Takeaway}}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        The mean also known as average of a data set is the sum of all values divided by the total number of values.
    </p>
    <p>
        Formula for Mean is given by:
    </p>
    <p>
        <m> \textbf{Mean} = \frac{\textbf{sum of all values}}{\textbf{Total number of values}}</m>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A farmer recorded the number of oranges picked from <m>45</m> trees in his orchard. The number of apples picked from each tree is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>50, 55, 60, 52, 48, 54, 58, 60, 55, 57, 53, 50, 52, 56, 55</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>54, 55, 58, 60, 57, 54, 53, 55, 58, 60, 55, 52, 50, 53, 56</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m> 60, 52, 50, 55, 57, 59, 54, 53, 56, 50, 55, 58, 52, 57, 54</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Find the mean number of oranges picked per tree.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>

            <p>
                Add all the apple counts
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>50+55+60+52+48+54+58+60+</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>55+57+53+50+52+56+54+</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>55+58+60+52+50+55+57</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>+59+54+53+56+50+55+58+52+57</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>+54+60+55+52+50+53+56</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>+55+58+60+57+54+53+55</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>=2467</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                Divide by the total number of trees <m>45</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Mean} = \frac{2467}{45} = 54.82</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                The mean number of apples picked per tree is <m>54.82</m>. 
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
        <m>{\color{black} \textbf{Median of Data}}</m>
    </p>

    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>{\color{black} \textbf{Work in groups}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Taita secondary school football team coach recorded the heights (in cm) of <m>25</m> players on the team:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>175, 178, 180, 182, 185, 187, 190, 192, 195, 197, 200, 202,</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>205, 207, 210, 212, 215, 217, 220, 222, 225, 227, 230, 232, 235</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the median height of the players.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Explain what the median represents in this scenario
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m>{\color{black} \textbf{Key Takeaway}}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        The item in the middle is the median when the items in a data set are sorted in ascending order.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A bakery recorded the number of loaves of bread sold each day for <m>30</m> days. The numbers are:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>50, 55, 60, 52, 58, 65, 70, 68, 72, 75, 80, 85, 90, 95, 100,</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>105, 110, 98, 92, 88, 78, 66, 62, 54, 59, 74, 82, 87, 97, 102</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Find the median number of loaves sold per day.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>

            <p>
                Arrange the data in ascending order
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>50, 52, 54, 55, 58, 59, 60, 62, 65, 66, 68, 70, 72, 74, 75, </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>78, 80, 82, 85, 87, 88, 90, 92, 95, 97, 98, 100, 102, 105, 110</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Find the middle values
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since there are <m>30</m> values (even number), the median is the average of the <m>\text{15th}</m> and <m>\text{16th}</m> values.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\text{15th}</m> value = <m> 75</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\text{16th}</m> value = <m>78</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m> \text{Median} = \frac{75 + 78}{2} = 76.5</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                The median number of loaves sold per day is <m>76.5</m>.
            </p>
        
        </solution>
    </example>
